INSERT INTO `wp_options` VALUES(185, 0, '_transient_dash_aa95765b5cc111c56d5993d476b1c2f0', '<div class="rss-widget"><ul><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/J6IkXUGU69Y/wordpress-optimization-guide-by-dreamhost'' title=''Dreamhost has a section on their Wiki explaining detailed ways on how to optimize WordPress using such tools as WP Super Cache, Nocache, Fcgi, and various combinations of the latter. I don’t understand the gobbily gook presented within the document but if you’re using your own dedicated server or VPS, these tips might be of interest to you. An aside but also [&hellip;]''>WPTavern: WordPress Optimization Guide By Dreamhost</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/sHixOaIMhXA/extensive-checklist-for-wordpress-3-3-that-all-developers-should-check'' title=''Andrew Nacin who is one of the core developers of WordPress has published an extensive field guide for developers regarding WordPress 3.3. The guide contains links to relevant articles and discussions on the WordPress developers blog such as admin bar API changes, Javascript and editor changes, Help screen along with API changes, etc. All developers should t [&hellip;]''>WPTavern: Extensive Checklist For WordPress 3.3 That All Developers Should Check</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~3/3EgeD6M0_0A/'' title=''WordPress 3.3 RC 2 has been released. The team feels that WordPress 3.3 is just about ready to be released, so this could very well be the last release candidate before 3.3 is officially released. If you’re a plugin or theme developer, it’s time to test your products against WordPress 3.3 before the rest of the world gets their hands on it. Andrew Nacin has  [&hellip;]''>Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress 3.3 RC 2 Released</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://nacin.com/2011/12/07/wordpress-3-3-field-guide-for-developers/'' title=''Last night, WordPress 3.3 Release Candidate 2 was released. As written in the release post, I think we’re really close to a final release. In preparation for that, I went on a tear yesterday and contributed to six posts for developers on our main development blog. The posts were a mixture of tutorials and API documentation what’s new and what’s changed in 3. [&hellip;]''>Andrew Nacin: WordPress 3.3 Field Guide for Developers</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/JI5dQ7p--U8/using-sidebars-as-menus'' title=''It’s an idea proposed by Ipstenu that might just work. The gist of her suggestion is to manage widgets similar to how we manage menus. Instead of all that fancy drag and drop stuff, we switch to a check box approach where users can check which widgets they want to have added to a particular sidebar. Judging by the comments left on that post, a number of peop [&hellip;]''>WPTavern: Using Sidebars As Menus?</a></li></ul></div>', 'no');
